\"List of existing trade unions\">unions and their contact details</a> on the website of the Certification Officer, the independent organisation responsible for the legal regulation of unions.</p>\n\n<p>You can also use the TUC&rsquo;s <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.worksmart.org.uk/unionfinder/\" title=\"Find a union\">interactive tool</a> to help you find a trade union in your workplace, or one which covers your type of job. </p>\n\n<h2>Trade union membership subscriptions</h2>\n<p>Your union will charge a union membership fee (&lsquo;membership sub&rsquo;) to finance the work of the union. This can be a flat rate for all employees or based on how much you&rsquo;re paid.</p>\n\n<h3>Paying your membership subs</h3>\n<p>You can pay your subs by:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>having the amount taken by your employer from your pay and sent to the union (otherwise known as &lsquo;check-off&rsquo;)</li>\n  <li>direct debit</li>\n  <li>cash</li>\n  <li>cheque</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Paying by check-off</h3>\n<p>Your employer isn&rsquo;t legally required to take union membership subs from your pay and send it to the union.  They can stop sending your membership subs unless your employment contract says they have to.</p>\n\n<p>Your employer can&rsquo;t take union membership subs from your pay without your written permission. Many trade unions will get your agreement to pay by check-off when you join, and forward it to your employer. </p>\n\n<p>You can also ask your employer in writing to stop taking money from your pay for check-off whenever you want. They must then stop taking subs from your pay as soon as it&rsquo;s possible.</p>\n\n<p>Your employer is responsible for making sure that any check-off payments they make are legal. </p>\n\n<h3>What to do if you have a problem</h3>\n<p>If you have a problem with your check-off payments, try to discuss the issue with your employer and your trade union first.</p>\n\n<p>If your trade union subscriptions are taken from your pay without your consent, you could make a complaint to an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"employment tribunal\">employment tribunal</a> against your employer. </p>\n\n<p>If your complaint is successful the employment tribunal can order your employer to pay you the value of the unauthorised payments.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/trade-union-membership-your-employment-rights","slug":"trade-union-membership-your-employment-rights","order":2,"title":"Trade union membership: your employment rights","body":"<p>You have the right to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>choose to join or not join a union</li>\n  <li>decide to leave or remain a member of a union</li>\n  <li>belong to the union you choose, even if it&rsquo;s not the one your employer negotiates with on pay, terms and conditions</li>\n  <li>belong to more than one union</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Your employer isn&rsquo;t allowed to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>offer you a benefit to leave a trade union</li>\n  <li>threaten to treat you unfairly if you don&rsquo;t leave a union</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Refusing to employ you for trade union membership reasons</h3>\n\n<p>An employer or employment agency isn&rsquo;t allowed to insist that you:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>join or leave a trade union</li>\n  <li>leave one union for another</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Dismissal for trade union membership reasons</h3>\n<p>Your employer isn&rsquo;t allowed to dismiss you or choose you for redundancy because you:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>are or want to be a union member </li>\n  <li>aren&rsquo;t or don&rsquo;t want to be a union member </li>\n  <li>took part or wanted to take part in union activities</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Other unfavourable treatment</h3>\n<p>Your employer mustn&rsquo;t treat you unfavourably (for example refusing you promotion or training opportunities) if you:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>join a union </li>\n  <li>take part in its meetings </li>\n  <li>leave a union</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>What to do if you have a problem</h2>\n<p>You may be able to use a grievance procedure or go to an <a href=\"/employment-tribunals\" title=\"employment tribunal\">employment tribunal</a>  if you think your employer has treated you unfairly because of your trade union membership.</p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/join-trade-union/role-of-your-trade-union-rep","slug":"role-of-your-trade-union-rep","order":3,"title":"Role of your trade union rep","body":"<p>A trade union representative (&lsquo;rep&rsquo;) is a union member who represents and gives advice to colleagues when they have problems at work. </p>\n\n<p>Trade union reps aren&rsquo;t paid but they do get paid time off to do their work as a rep.</p>\n\n<h2>What do union reps do?</h2>\n<p>Reps are there to:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>discuss any concerns you have about your employer</li>\n  <li>go with (&lsquo;accompany&rsquo;) you to disciplinary or grievance hearings with management</li>\n  <li>represent you in negotiations (&lsquo;collective bargaining&rsquo;) over your pay and terms and conditions of employment</li>\n  <li>meet with your employer to find solutions to workplace issues</li>\n  <li>develop the best possible health and safety procedures with your employer</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Employers must consult with union reps if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>there is going to be a business transfer or takeover</li>\n  <li>they are planning to make 20 or more people redundant within 90 days</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Your right to be accompanied</h2>\n\n<p>You have the right to be accompanied by your union rep to some meetings with management - eg if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you&rsquo;re facing a disciplinary charge</li>\n  <li>you wish to raise a grievance with your employer </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If your union rep can&rsquo;t attend, you may be able to rearrange the meeting or ask a work colleague to go with you.</p>\n\n<h2>Becoming a union rep</h2>\n<p>If you want to become a union rep, ask another rep in the workplace or contact your union through its website. Depending on union rules, you may be appointe