atter what has been previously agreed.</p>\n\n<h2>Compulsory maternity leave</h2>\n<p>If the employee isn&rsquo;t taking Statutory Maternity Leave, they must take 2 weeks off after the baby is born - or 4 weeks if they work in a factory.</p>\n\n<h2>Telling the employer about the pregnancy</h2>\n\n<p>Employees must tell their employer about the pregnancy at least 15 weeks before the beginning of the week the baby is due. </p>\n\n<p>If this isn&rsquo;t possible - eg because they didn&rsquo;t know they were pregnant - the employer must be told as soon as possible. </p>\n\n<p>Employees must also tell the employer when they want to start their <a href=\"/maternity-leave\" title=\"Statutory Maternity Leave\">Statutory Maternity Leave</a> and <a href=\"/statutory-maternity-pay\" title=\"Statutory Maternity Pay\">Pay</a>. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice info-notice\">\n<p>Employees can’t take time off for antenatal appointments until they’ve told the employer about the pregnancy.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Health and safety for pregnant employees</h2>\n\n<p>When the employee tells their employer they&rsquo;re pregnant, they should be prevented from exposure to any risks to protect them and the baby. </p>\n\n<p>Risks could be caused by:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>heavy lifting or carrying</li>\n  <li>standing or sitting for long periods without adequate breaks</li>\n  <li>exposure to toxic substances</li>\n  <li>long working hours</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>If the employer can&rsquo;t remove any risks (eg by offering suitable alternative work) they should <a href=\"/expenses-and-benefits-medical-suspension-payments\" title=\"suspension from work for medical reasons\">suspend the employee on full pay</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Pregnant employees who think they&rsquo;re at risk but their employer disagrees should talk to their health and safety or trade union representative. If your employer still refuses to do anything, talk to your doctor or contact the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hse.gov.uk/contact/index.htm\" title=\"Contact the Health and Safety Executive\">Health and Safety Executive.</a></p>\n\n","alternative_title":""},"updated_at":"2012-10-25T15:32:16+00:00","tags":[{"title":"Your rights at work and trade unions","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working%2Frights-trade-unions.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes health and safety, accidents at work and joining a trade union","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working%2Frights-trade-unions","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working/rights-trade-unions"},"parent":{"title":"Working, jobs and pensions","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/working.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes holidays and finding a job","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=working","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/working"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Trade unions and workers rights","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/employing-people%2Ftrade-unions.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes industrial action and recognising trade unions","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=employing-people%2Ftrade-unions","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/employing-people/trade-unions"},"parent":{"title":"Employing people","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/employing-people.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes pay, contracts and hiring","short_description":null,"type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=employing-people","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/employing-people"},"parent":null}},{"title":"Having a child, parenting and adoption","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages%2Fchild-adoption.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Legal rights, birth certificates, parental rights and child maintenance","short_description":"","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages%2Fchild-adoption","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages/child-adoption"},"parent":{"title":"Births, deaths, marriages and care","id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/tags/births-deaths-marriages.json","web_url":null,"details":{"description":"Includes civil partnerships, splitting up and Lasting Power of Attorney","short_description":"","type":"section"},"content_with_tag":{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/with_tag.json?tag=births-deaths-marriages","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/browse/births-deaths-marriages"},"parent":null}}],"related":[{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/maternity-leave.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/maternity-leave","title":"Maternity Leave","format":"programme","details":{"need_id":"1862","business_proposition":false,"description":"Maternity leave and checking your eligibility to take it - including Ordinary Maternity Leave, Additional Maternity Leave and your right to return to work\r\n"},"updated_at":"2012-10-25T10:51:54+00:00"},{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/maternity-benefits.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/maternity-benefits","title":"Maternity pay entitlement","format":"smart-answer","details":{"need_id":"1660","business_proposition":false,"description":"Tool to work out if you qualify for Statutory Maternity Pay (SMP), Maternity Allowance (MA) or other benefits and what money you could get"},"updated_at":"2012-11-09T10:50:26+00:00"}]},{"id":"https://www.gov.uk/api/reasonable-adjustments-for-disabled-workers.json","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/reasonable-adjustments-for-disabled-workers","title":"Reasonable adjustments for disabled workers","format":"answer","details":{"need_id":"B89","business_proposition":true,"description":"Employers must make reasonable adjustments to make sure disabled workers are not seriously disadvantaged when doing their jobs ","body":"\n<div class=\"summary\">\n<p>Employers must make reasonable adjustments to make sure disabled workers are not seriously disadvantaged when doing their jobs.</p>\n</div>\n\n<p>Disabled workers are <a href=\"/rights-disabled-person/employment\" title=\"Disabled workers' rights\">protected by the Equality Act 2010</a>. In Northern Ireland workers are \n<a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.equalityni.org/sections/default.asp?cms=Employers_Legislation&amp;cmsid=129_618&amp;id=618&amp;secid=3\" title=\"Find out about the Disability Discrimination Act\">protected by the Disability Discrimination Act 1995.</a> </p>\n\n<p>Workers must be given access to training opportunities, recreation and refreshment facilities.</p>\n\n<p>Employers have to make reasonable adjustments even if they don&rsquo;t employ the person directly - this includes contract workers, trainees, apprentices and business partners.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"/access-to-work\" title=\"Access to Work: financial support for disabled workers\">Funding</a> may be available to help with some costs involved in making reasonable adjustments.</p>\n\n<h2>What reasonable adjustments are</h2>\n\n<p>Examples could involve:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>doing things another way - eg allowing someone with social anxiety disorder to have their own desk instead of hot-desking</li>\n  <li>making physical changes - eg installing a ramp for a wheelchair user or an audio-visual fire alarm for a deaf person</li>\n  <li>letting a disabled person work somewhere else - eg on the ground floor for a wheelchair user</li>\n  <li>changing their equipment - eg providing a special keyboard if they have arthritis</li>\n  <li>allowing employees who become disabled to make a phased return to work - eg working flexible hours or part-time</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>More advice</h2>\n<p>You can get advice on reasonable adjustments from the Disability Employment Adviser (<abbr title=\"Disability Employment Adviser\">DEA</abbr>) at <a href=\"/contact-jobcentre-plus\" title=\"Contact Jobce